'''三十枚錢幣<!--三十枚銀幣-->'''（Thirty pieces of silver）是[[耶穌|耶穌]]的門徒[[加略人猶大|加略人猶大]]出賣耶穌所得到的報酬，記載於[[新約聖經|新約聖經]][[馬太福音|馬太福音]] 26:15 <ref>{{bibleverse|Matthew|26:15|NIV}}</ref>。猶大在[[最後的晚餐|最後的晚餐]]前密訪了大祭司，並同意以三十枚錢幣的價格出賣耶穌，但事後猶大後悔不已，要把錢還給大祭司，大祭司沒有接受，後來猶大上吊死亡，大祭司用三十枚錢幣買了{{le|窯匠的地|Akeldama}}。

馬太福音認為購買窯匠的地之事，應驗了舊約先知[[撒迦利亞|撒迦利亞]]的預言<ref>Vincent P. Branick, ''Understanding the New Testament and Its Message'', (Paulist Press, 1998), pp. 126–128.</ref><ref>Frederick Dale Bruner, Matthew: A Commentary (Eerdmans, 2004), p. 710</ref>

三十枚錢幣常出現在藝術作品中，用來描述[[耶穌受難記|耶穌受難]]。三十枚錢幣也常出現在文學中，以及西方的日常用語中，以表達「{{le|出賣|Selling out}}」，為了個人利益，破壞信任、友誼或是對人的忠誠。

==聖經敘述==
根據[[馬太福音|馬太福音]]的敘述，[[加略人猶大|加略人猶大]]是[[耶稣|耶稣]]的[[使徒_(基督教)|十二門徒]]之一。他在[[最后的晚餐|最后的晚餐]]之前去找了祭司長，{{tsl|en|Bargain of Judas|Bargain of Judas|同意}}交付耶穌，祭司長給了他三十枚錢幣<ref>{{tsl|en|R. T. France||R. T. France}}, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=0ruP6J_XPCEC The Gospel of Matthew]'' (Grand Rapids: Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2007), 976–979.</ref>。之後耶穌在[[客西马尼园|客西马尼园]]，猶大用[[犹大之吻|親嘴問安]]告訴其他人哪一個才是耶穌，因此[[耶稣被捕|耶稣被捕]]<ref>France, ''The Gospel of Matthew'', 1012.</ref>，

根據[[馬太福音|馬太福音]]27章所述，猶大很後悔，將錢還給祭司長，然後上吊自殺。祭司長認為這三十枚錢幣是[[血腥钱|血腥钱]]，不能放在[[第二圣殿|圣殿]]內<ref>https://www.biblica.com/bible/niv/matthew/27/</ref>，因此用這筆錢買了{{le|窯匠的地|Akeldama}}<ref>Daniel J. Harrington, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bNf13S3k2w0C The Gospel of Matthew]'' (Collegeville, Minnesota: Liturgical Press, 1991), 384–387.</ref>。

在[[使徒行传|使徒行传]]一章17-20節有另一段有關猶大之死的記載。這段文字是記錄[[彼得_(使徒)|彼得]]所說的話：「這人用作惡的工價買了一塊田，以後身子仆倒，肚腹崩裂，腸子都流出來。」<ref>[http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=acts%201:18 Acts 1:18].</ref>。雖然[[路加福音|路加福音]]（一般認為{{tsl|en|Authorship of Luke–Acts|路加福音和使徒行傳的作者|和使徒行傳的作者相同}}）在22章3-6節提到猶大和祭司長、守殿官約定了賣耶穌的報酬，但沒有寫出金額，不像馬太福音所述的，之前就將錢給了猶大<ref>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=luke+22%3A3-6&version=NIV Luke 22:3–6]</ref>。

==錢幣的種類==<!---第一段和英文版有些不同, 後面還多了一個表格-->
[[File:C+B-Stater-StaterOfAntioch.PNG|thumb]]的[[斯塔特|斯塔特]]（Stater）貨幣可能是三十枚錢幣中所提及的錢幣]]
[[File:C+B-Shekel-FigC-TyrianHalfShekel.PNG|thumb]]
馬太福音26:15所用的字（ἀργύρια, argyria）意思就是「銀幣」<ref>[http://www.blueletterbible.org/lang/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?Strongs=G694&t=KJV ''Thayer's Greek-English Lexicon of the New Testament'', 1889.]</ref>，學者對於當時所用的硬幣種類還沒有共識。{{tsl|en|Donald Wiseman|Donald Wiseman}}提出了二種可能，銀幣可能是[[泰尔|泰尔]]的[[四德拉克馬|四德拉克馬]]，一般會稱為{{tsl|en|Tyrian shekel|推罗舍客勒}}（14克，其中含銀94%）或是[[安条克|安条克]]的[[斯塔特|斯塔特]]（15克，其中含銀75%），上面有[[奥古斯都|奥古斯都]]的像<ref>D. J. Wiseman, ''Illustrations from Biblical Archaeology'' (London: Tyndale Press, 1958), 8789.</ref>。其他的可能包括有[[托勒密王國|托勒密王國]]的四德拉克馬（13.5 ± 1 g ，含銀25%）<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.coin-newbies.com/articles/bible.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020618223339/http://coin-newbies.com/articles/bible.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 June 2002 |title=So-called 'Coins of the Bible' |author=Michael E. Marotta |year=2001 |access-date=11 Sep 2010 }}</ref>。一金衡盎司是31.1035克，若用$17.06/oz的價格（2016年12月12日的收盤價）計算，「三十枚錢幣」約對應現今的美元185至216元。

推罗舍客勒的重量等於四個雅典的[[希腊德拉克马|德拉克马]]，約14 克，以較早期使用的11 克以色列舍客勒要重，不過在宗教稅捐上視為是等效的<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/FlJosephus/coins.htm|title=Ancient Jewish Coins Related to the Works of Josephus}}, citing David Hendin's Guide to Biblical Coins and Y. Meshorer's Ancient Jewish Coinage.</ref>。因為羅馬的銀幣中只有80%的[[銀|銀]]，耶路撒冷的{{tsl|en|temple tax|聖殿稅}}要求要用銀含量較高（94%以上）的推罗舍客勒來繳納，在聖經（馬太福音21:12或是其他平行經文）中，在聖殿中兌換銀錢的人就是將一般的羅馬貨幣兌換為推罗舍客勒<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www-scf.usc.edu/~ciccone/html/role%20of%20coins%20in%20revolt.htm|title=The role of coins in the First Revolt|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029045733/http://www-scf.usc.edu/~ciccone/html/role%20of%20coins%20in%20revolt.htm|archive-date=2008-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dqhall59.com/fish_and_coin.htm|title=Israel photos III}}</ref>。

在[[亚历山大大帝|亚历山大大帝]]（以及其推動的[[科林斯|科林斯]][[斯塔特|斯塔特]]）之前，希臘世界最常使用的硬幣就是在西元前五世紀[[雅典|雅典]]的[[四德拉克馬|四德拉克馬]]硬幣。其正面是[[雅典娜|雅典娜]]的頭盔式胸圍，反面是老鷹。在日常使用上會稱為{{lang|grc|γλαῦκες}} ''glaukes''（老鷹）<ref>{{LSJ|glau/c|γλαύξ|shortref}}.</ref>。四德拉克馬是在各個希臘的鑄幣廠，以不同的重量標準鑄製。最常使用的標準是Athenian或Attic標準，重量約超過4.3 克。一德拉克馬約是有技術的勞工一天的工資<ref>[[修昔底德|Thucydides]], ''[[伯罗奔尼撒战争史|History of the Peloponnesian War]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text.jsp?doc=thuc.%203.17 3.17.4].</ref>。因此30個四德拉克馬硬幣，約等於四個月的工資。

中古時期有一些宗教組織將古希臘[[罗得岛|罗得岛]]的硬幣當作三十枚錢幣的樣本。硬幣的正面是太陽神[[赫利俄斯|赫利俄斯]]的頭像，周圍有向外放射的光芒。他們將這些光芒解釋為代表耶穌的[[荆棘王冠|荆棘王冠]]。

未入圣典的''Narrative of Joseph of Arimathea''記錄的是猶大的報酬是三十塊金子，不是銀幣<ref name="ehrman-plese 553">{{cite book |title=The Apocryphal Gospels: Texts and Translations |last1=Ehrman |first1=Bart |last2=Plese |first2=Zlatko |author-link1=Bart D. Ehrman |author-link2=Zlatko Pleše |year=2011 |publisher=[[牛津大學出版社|Oxford University Press]] |location=New York |isbn=9780199732104 |page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780199732104/page/553 553] |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780199732104|url-access=registration |quote=exchange for thirty pieces. }}</ref>。

==Theological interpretation==
In [[撒迦利亞書|Zechariah]] 11:12–13, 30 pieces of silver is the price [[撒迦利亚|Zechariah]] receives for his labour. He takes the coins and throws them "to the potter". {{tsl|en|Klaas Schilder||Klaas Schilder}} notes that Zechariah's payment indicates an assessment of his worth, as well as his dismissal.<ref>{{tsl|en|Klaas Schilder||Klaas Schilder}}, ''Christ in His Suffering'' (Grand Rapids: Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing, 1938), 74.</ref> In [[出埃及記|Exodus]] 21:32, 30 pieces of silver was the price of a slave, so while Zechariah calls the amount a "handsome price" (Zechariah 11:13), this could be [[挖苦|sarcasm]]. {{tsl|en|Barry Webb||Barry Webb}}, however, regards it as a "considerable sum of money."<ref>{{tsl|en|Barry Webb||Barry Webb}}, ''The Message of Zechariah'' (Bible Speaks Today; Nottingham: Inter-Varsity Press, 2003), 151.</ref>

Schilder suggests that these 30 pieces of silver then get "bandied back and forth by the Spirit of [[圣经预言|Prophecy]]."<ref>Schilder, ''Christ in His Suffering'', 71.</ref> When the chief priests decide to buy a {{tsl|en|Akeldama||field}} with the returned money, Matthew says that this fulfilled "what was spoken by [[耶利米|Jeremiah]] the prophet." Namely, "They took the thirty silver coins, the price set on him by the people of Israel, and they used them to buy the potter's field, as the Lord commanded me" (Matthew 27:9–10). Although many scholars see Jeremiah's name as included in error,<ref>[[约翰·加尔文|John Calvin]], for example, says that "the passage itself plainly shows that the name of Jeremiah has been put down by mistake, instead of Zechariah, for in Jeremiah we find nothing of this sort, nor any thing that even approaches to it." John Calvin, ''[http://www.ccel.org/ccel/calvin/calcom33.ii.xxxvi.html Commentary on a Harmony of the Evangelists, Matthew, Mark and Luke]''.</ref> Jeremiah's purchase of a field in [[耶利米書|Jeremiah]] 32 may indicate that both prophets are in mind.<ref>{{tsl|en|Craig S. Keener||Craig S. Keener}}, ''The Gospel of Matthew: A Socio-Rhetorical Commentary'' (Grand Rapids: Eerdmans, 2009), 657.</ref> {{tsl|en|Craig Blomberg||Craig Blomberg}} argues that Matthew is using [[预表|typology]] in his quotation, rather than "any kind of single or double fulfillment of actual predictive prophecy." According to Blomberg, Matthew is telling his readers that, "like Jeremiah and Zechariah, Jesus attempts to lead his people with a prophetic and pastoral ministry, but instead he ends up suffering innocently at their hands."<ref>{{tsl|en|Craig Blomberg||Craig L. Blomberg}}, "Matthew," in G. K. Beale and D. A. Carson (eds.), ''Commentary on the New Testament Use of the Old Testament'' (Grand Rapids: Baker Academic, 2007), 96.</ref> {{tsl|en|William Hendriksen||William Hendriksen}} argues that Matthew is referring to Jeremiah 19.<ref>{{tsl|en|William Hendriksen||William Hendriksen}}, ''Exposition of the Gospel According to Matthew'' (Grand Rapids: Baker, 1973), 948.</ref>

Blomberg also suggests that Matthew may also be saying that "Jesus' death is a ransom, the price paid to secure a slave's freedom," and that the use of the [[血腥钱|blood money]] to buy a {{tsl|en|Potter's field||burial ground for foreigners}} (Matthew 27:7) may hint at the idea that "Jesus' death makes salvation possible for all the peoples of the world, including the {{tsl|en|Gentiles||Gentiles}}."<ref>Blomberg, "Matthew", 97.</ref>

The 1877 Handy Book for Bible Readers states that "Argurion, argenteus, denarius. This word occurs in two passages--(A) the account of the betrayal of our Lord for "thirty pieces of silver" (Matt. xxvi. 15; xxvii. 3, 5, 6, 9). These have usually been considered to be denarii, but on no sufficient ground. The parallel passage in Zechariah (xi. 12, 13), is translated "thirty [pieces] of silver"; but which should doubtless be read, "thirty shekels of silver", whilst it is observable that "thirty shekels of silver" was the price of blood to be paid in the case of a servant accidentally killed (Exod. xxi. 32). The passage may therefore be explained as "thirty shekels of silver", not current shekels, but tetradrachms of the Attic standard of the Greek cities of Syria and Phoencia. These tetradrachms were common at the time of our Lord, and of them the stater was a specimen."

==Relics and depiction in art==
[[File:Judas_Returning_the_Thirty_Silver_Pieces_-_Rembrandt.jpg|thumb]]'s ''Judas Returning the Thirty Silver Pieces'', 1629.]]
Judas is often shown in narrative scenes from the [[耶穌受難|Passion]] holding the silver in a bag or purse, where they serve as an {{tsl|en|Emblem||attribute}} to identify him.  As one of the "{{tsl|en|Arma Christi||Instruments of the Passion}}" the Thirty Pieces by themselves often feature in groups of the Instruments, especially in the late Middle Ages, although they are one of the less commonly chosen elements of the group.  Sometimes a money bag is used in depictions; otherwise a hand holding the coins, or two hands, showing the counting-out.<ref>{{tsl|en|Gertrud Schiller||Gertrud Schiller}}, ''Iconography of Christian Art, Vol. II'' (trans. Janet Seligman; London: Lund Humphries, 1972), 190–196.</ref>
[[File:VA23Oct10_100-crop.jpg|thumb]], London)]]

A number of "Judas-pennies", ancient coins said to be from the original thirty, were treated as [[圣髑|relic]]s in the Middle Ages, and were believed to help in difficult cases of childbirth.<ref>G. F. Hill, "Coins and Medals (Western)," in James Hastings and John A. Selbie, (eds.), ''Encyclopedia of Religion and Ethics, Part 6'' (Whitefish, Montana: Kessinger Publishing, 2003), [https://books.google.com/books?id=INJI4FGeLpYC&pg=PA703 703].</ref><ref>Johannes A. Mol, Klaus Militzer, and Helen J. Nicholson, ''The Military Orders and the Reformation: Choices, state building, and the weight of tradition'' (Hilversum: Uitgeverij Verloren, 2006), [https://books.google.com/books?id=IrJHCrTvOr0C&pg=PA287 287].</ref>  As a minor component of the Instruments, and one whose survival was hard to explain given the Biblical account of the use of the money, the relics, and their depiction in art, both appear from the 14th century, later than more important elements like the [[荆棘王冠|Crown of Thorns]] or [[圣枪|Spear of Longinus]].  This was as a result of new styles of devotions, led by the [[方济各会|Franciscans]] in particular, which promoted  contemplation of the Passion episode by episode, as in the [[苦路|Stations of the Cross]].<ref>Schiller, ''Iconography of Christian Art, Vol. II'', 190–191</ref>  The stone on which the coins were said to have been counted out was in the [[拉特朗宫|Lateran Palace]] in Rome.<ref>Piero Della Francesca, ''Enigma of Piero'', (2nd ed., trans. Martin Ryle and Kate Soper; London: Verso Books, 2001), [https://books.google.com/books?id=mKEGUiGdKHYC&pg=PA68 68].</ref>

A [[锡拉库萨|Syracusan]] [[古希腊钱币|decadrachm]] held at the [[漢特博物館|Hunt Museum]], [[利默里克|Limerick]] is one such coin claimed to be one of the thirty: inscribed on the mount is ''Quia precium sanguinis est'' ([[拉丁语|Latin]]: "This is the price of blood").<ref>http://www.huntmuseum.com/collection/collection-items/mg-034.aspx</ref>

==Literary references==
[[File:Dekadrachm_of_Syracuse_one_of_the_thirty_pieces_of_silver_obverse.jpg|left]])]]
The 30 pieces are used in Christian literature on the betrayal of Jesus, as in the poem ''Thirty Pieces of Silver'' by William Blane:

<blockquote>
"Thirty pieces of silver"<br>
Burns on the traitor's brain;<br>
"Thirty pieces of silver!<br>
Oh! it is hellish gain!"<ref>William Blane, "Thirty Pieces of Silver," in ''[https://archive.org/details/silentlandandoth00blanuoft The Silent Land and other Poems]'', (London: E. Stock, 1906), 149.</ref>
</blockquote>

or as in the poem ''Matthew XXVII:9'' by [[豪尔赫·路易斯·博尔赫斯|Jorge Luis Borges]]:

<blockquote>
The coin fell on my hollow hand.<br>
I could not bear it, although it was light,<br>
and I let it fall. It was all in vain.<br>
The other said: "There are still twenty nine."<ref>Jorge Luis Borges, "Matthew XXVII:9," in ''La moneda de hierro'', (Buenos Aires: 1976).</ref>
</blockquote>

The phrase "30 pieces of silver" is used more generally to describe a price at which people [[Selling_out|sell out]].<ref name=dict/> In [[費奧多爾·米哈伊洛維奇·陀思妥耶夫斯基|Dostoyevsky]]'s ''[[罪与罚|Crime and Punishment]]'', it is echoed in the 30 [[卢布|rouble]]s which the character Sonia earns for selling herself.<ref>Fyodor Dostoyevsky, ''Crime and punishment'', (Ware: Wordsworth Classics, 2000), 17. Note by Keith Carabine on [https://books.google.com/books?id=bAtLzdTvzJcC&pg=PA470 p. 470.]</ref><ref>William J. Leatherbarrow, ''The Cambridge Companion to Dostoevskii'', (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2002), [https://books.google.com/books?id=4Lf0xf3a6s4C&pg=PA98 98].</ref> In the folk-song ''{{tsl|en|King John and the Bishop||King John and the Bishop}}'', the bishop's answer to the [[謎語|riddle]] of how much the king is worth is 29 pieces of silver, as no king is worth more than Jesus. In [[威廉·莎士比亚|Shakespeare]]'s play ''{{tsl|en|Henry IV, Part 2||Henry IV, Part 2}}'', the mistress of Falstaff asks "and didst thou not kiss me, and bid me fetch thee thirty shillings?"<ref name=dict>{{Cite book| year=1992 | title = A Dictionary of biblical tradition in English literature | editor=David L. Jeffrey | publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing | isbn=978-0-8028-3634-2 | page=766 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zD6xVr1CizIC&pg=PA766&dq=%22thirty+pieces%22}}</ref> The story "Treasure Trove" by {{tsl|en|F. Tennyson Jesse||F. Tennyson Jesse}} relates the rediscovery in modern times of the thirty pieces of silver and how they drive men to kill in varied forms including murder, manslaughter, homicide, euthanasia and suicide.

==現代的用法==
現代在歐美，會將「三十枚錢幣」這個詞用來譴責政治家或是藝術家{{tsl|en|selling out|出賣}}了自身的原則或是理想，「三十枚錢幣」也用在文學中，代表「背叛」。例如在[[1975年澳大利亚宪政危机|1975年澳大利亚宪政危机]]之後，許多住在总督[[约翰·克尔_(总督)|约翰·克尔]]出生地的居民送給總督三十枚錢幣<ref>The residents of the street in Balmain where he had been born posted him thirty pieces of silver. http://www.australian-politics-books.com/ccp0-prodshow/the-real-joh-kerr-richard-hall.html</ref>，許多人認為克尔解散了同為工黨的政府，需為這次的宪政危机負責。另外一次提到「三十枚錢幣」是在[[2009年联合国气候变化大会|2009年联合国气候变化大会]]中，[[圖瓦盧|圖瓦盧]]的發言人批評[[哥本哈根协议|哥本哈根协议]]說：「看起來像是我們為了三十枚錢幣背叛了我們的人民以及未來……我們的未來不是拿來買賣的。」<ref>{{cite news |title=Future not for sale: climate deal rejected |publisher=ABC News |date=19 Dec 2009 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/19/2776604.htm |access-date=11 Sep 2010}}</ref>。

2016年時，{{tsl|en|Texas Attorney General|德克薩斯州總檢察長}}{{tsl|en|Ken Paxton|肯·帕克斯頓}}對{{tsl|en|Obama administration|歐巴馬政府}}提起訴訟，要阻止{{tsl|en|Gender identity under Title IX|基於美國《教育修正案》第IX條下的性別認同法令}}實施，此法案提到公私立的教育機構允許跨性別學生依其對自身的性別認同來使用浴室。該法令指出：若學校不遵守法令，可能無法取得聯邦的資助<ref>{{cite news |title=Dear Colleague Letter |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/file/850986/download |agency=Department of Justice |date=May 13, 2016}}</ref>。德州州長對美國教育部的回應是，教育部可以「省下這三十枚錢幣」{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}。帕克斯頓在其他的場合也多次用過這個詞。

2021年時在[[第二次特朗普弹劾案|第二次特朗普弹劾案]]中，有十名共和黨的[[美国众议院|眾議員]]支持此弹劾案，福音派牧師[[葛福臨|葛福臨]]譴責這些議員，認為[[美國眾議院議長|美國眾議院議長]][[南希·佩洛西|南希·佩洛西]]給了他們「三十枚錢幣」<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/franklin-graham-republicans-trump-impeachment_n_6001ebb6c5b6ffcab9644320|title=Evangelist Compares Republicans Who Voted For Trump’s Impeachment To Judas|author1=Carol Kurvilla|publisher=[[赫芬顿邮报|HuffPost]]|date=January 15, 2021}}</ref>。

